{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640870"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:19:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:19:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17844"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17844"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10558"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72569"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10558"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17844"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58039"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5099"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24618"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24622"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72569"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EInsulin is a hormone that helps regulate blood glucose levels. After an injection of insulin, blood glucose levels decrease as the hormone facilitates the uptake of glucose into cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following time intervals best represents when blood glucose levels typically reach their lowest point after an insulin injection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["15 minutes","30 minutes","45 minutes","60 minutes","75 minutes"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAfter an insulin injection, blood glucose levels typically reach their lowest point around \u003Cstrong\u003E30 minutes\u003C/strong\u003E. This is due to the rapid action of insulin facilitating glucose uptake into cells, thereby lowering blood glucose levels. The exact timing can vary based on the type of insulin used and individual patient factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E15 minutes\u003C/strong\u003E - This is generally too soon for the glucose nadir after insulin injection\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E45 minutes\u003C/strong\u003E - While possible, the nadir is more commonly observed at 30 minutes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E60 minutes\u003C/strong\u003E - This is typically beyond the usual time for the glucose nadir\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E75 minutes\u003C/strong\u003E - This is generally too late for the glucose nadir after insulin injection\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["After insulin injection, blood glucose levels typically reach their lowest point around 30 to 60 minutes.","The timing of glucose nadir can vary depending on the type of insulin used and individual patient factors."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Chandel NS. Carbohydrate Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Jan 4;13(1):a040568. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040568. PMID: 33397651; PMCID: PMC7778149"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58039"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17844"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/item